body:
I think it would be cleanest to self-define HWND always, and pull in WGL stuff only if `GLFW_EXPOSE_NATIVE_WGL` is given. It might be possible to do that without including the entirety of windows.h, but I'm afraid I don't know (`wingdi.h`??). `WIN32_LEAN_AND_MEAN` would at least help to limit the fallout.

One other concern is how the header will interact with user code that wants to include `windows.h` for other reasons. If the user includes `glfw3native.h` before including `windows.h`, us having defined `HWND` already will probably cause errors, and visa versa. The main glfw header requires that you include it *after* `windows.h` already, but I don't think the documentation mentions this for glfw3native.h...

@elmindreda is this a change you would want to make? I don't use native access at all; maybe users are relying on it to include the whole of windows.h?
